node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by A Safe Place Inside Your Head on September 19, 2021 tagging @tanner_hamilton22. May be a cartoon of 1 person and text that says 'classic symptoms of mental illness parents Is this laziness? 百絲事典'.

node.text:
My father always thought me and my brother were lazy…never in my 29 years of existence and even today will he recognize my mental health. All it’s done is commit to me stopping the generational trauma that’s come with that to ensure my daughter always has an open forum to talk to me about things. Parents, please take the time to listen to your children. The world is a hard and scary place right now and even taking the time to meet they where they are at can mean the world. I know it’s all I needed when I was a little kid. - @tanner_hamilton22 
.
.
.
.

.

Its easy to become frustrated when dealing with someone you're so familiar with but its integral to their growth that you are patient & supportive'.

node.text:
My family has been awesome through it all. Through being in mental health health hospitals, struggling through life events and trying to grow as being a father I can say my parents have definitely been patient and I feel lucky to have them. Being patient in situations is important but also is setting boundaries. Make sure no one takes advantage of your niceness/patience. - @tanner_hamilton22

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by A Safe Place Inside Your Head in Austin, Texas. May be an image of text that says 'naly @chikenwiener not gonna lie it is really annyoing having to listen to my own thoughts Cant ever get a moment of peace in here Û'.

node.text:
Today has been a mind disaster of overthinking and anxiety. 

I am exhausted from the feelings of self loathing, and depression and the general anxiety that is overwhelming today. 

So tonight I said no to a thing, was ok with a cancelled plan and spent the evening alone, listening to ASMR and talking to my dog and doing some monotonous chores. My brain 🧠 is finally calmed down. 

As a general rule I’m easily overstimulated by a lot of noise and have a tendency to disassociate in response to that. I’m trying harder to notice the behavior and not fall off into that space and stay present. 

Tonight I did a good job of calming myself down.

What do you do when the mind chatter gets too loud? - @therealjoirizarry 

📸 @chikenwiener on Twitter 
.
.
.
.
.
#mindfuck #disassociation #calmthemind #calmthechaos #racingthoughts😣 #overstimulatedbrain #mentalillness #mentalhealthmemes🖤 #anxietyproblems #suicideawarenessmonth  #nopeaceofmind #asafeplaceinsideyourhead

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by A Safe Place Inside Your Head in Austin, Texas. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '@svmv_ @svmv Advice I got from my therapist today; If trom your mental health is starting to affect your physical health. Treat yourself ike you're sick. Minimum of 24hrs to yourself. Nap as much as you can. Drink plenty of liquids. Catch up on movies you've wanted to watch. The world can wait.'.

node.text:
I’m not a therapist but here’s the advice I give to you today. 

Your physical health and mental health effect each other completely. If you’re feeling physically run down there’s a good chance your mental health is suffering. 

If you’re feeling mentally unwell, I’m sure your physical body is feeling it too. See how that works? 

As we head into the weekend, take this therapists 👈 advice and treat your mentally unwell body the same as you would if you were sick. Rest, and be gentle with yourself. Binge watch something. Eat comforting foods.  The world can wait, right now your mental health needs some attention. 

I hope you heal - @therealjoirizarry 

📸 @svmv_ on Twitter 
.
.
.
.
.
#heal #takecareofyourself  #mentalhealthmatters #mentalhealthadvocate #depression #anxietysupport  #mentalhealthmemes🖤 #traumahealing #healingjourney💚 #mentalhealthrecovery #suicideawarenessmonth #asafeplaceinsideyourhead

node.text:
Posted this to my personal Instagram cause I’m suffering from a lot of self hate/loathing today but this account is like a diary to me so I’m just gunna rant a second. My potential relationships effect my mental health so much. Everyone is deserving of love, even if us ourselves don’t think so. I can be so hard on myself. I beat myself up constantly. Lately I’ve had thoughts of “am I good enough”, “am I ugly/not good looking”. Things cross my mind that are so negative but I have to put the love into myself that I want from others. This is me rambling because I am struggling today, I hope everyone has had a good day. - @tanner_hamilton22

node.text:
@katies.self.care.diaries is awesome. Neurodiversity is something I feel like needs to be talked about more.  Being being diagnosed with ADHD I struggled a lot to understand the world around me…once I saw the right DRs and got the right help it changed my life. I hate self diagnosing and I think it’s bad but I do believe that if you think you need help, then seek it. Reach out and research and talk to professionals who can either guide you to the right treatments or place your mind at ease by letting you know it’s perfectly normal. You aren’t alone and we are here for you. We love and appreciate you and we definitely want to bring more awareness to this topic!! - @tanner_hamilton22 
.
.
.
.
.
📸 = @katies.self.care.diaries

node.text:
My anxiety always plays tricks on me…constantly making me think up the worst scenarios. Following people like @anxietyjosh have helped me tremendously. Managing anxiety is hard to do and if you live with it every day just know I think you are so brave and I’m so proud of you for continuing to fight the good fight against it. Some things that have helped me with my anxiety are therapy, grounding techniques along with being honest with my friends and family about things that give me anxiety or triggers and getting reassurance from them when I feel anxiety. I think one thing I failed at doing was telling people “I don’t feel comfortable doing that, it’s going to make me feel anxious”. Once I set that boundary with people, it changed my life. I hope you all have an amazing day. - @tanner_hamilton22

node.text:
I am impulsive AF. 

I’m not clinically diagnosed with any mental health problems, so I won’t call myself someone with ADHD or OCD, but I know I’m prone to the traits of someone diagnosed with those mental health issues. 

Thankfully now that I don’t drink anymore ( eight years sober 🤟🏽) my impulsivity is more manageable. Im more aware when I overspend, or get in random arguments with people on the internet over basically nothing. I’m trying to set boundaries for myself and limit this impulsive behavior. 

How do you calm yourself the fuck down? @therealjoirizarry 

📸 @adhdangsty

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by A Safe Place Inside Your Head on September 15, 2021 tagging @tanner_hamilton22. May be a meme of text that says 'When you suffer from depression and somebody tells you to just cheer up.. My goodness, what an idea. Why didn't I think of that ?'.

node.text:
Posted this on my personal and thought more people may need to see this….if you are helping someone do you best to not say “cheer up” because it’s definitely the wrong way to approach the situation in my opinion. Sometimes I just need to vent and want someone to listen, I don’t really even need advice. I just need to hear the words outside of my head if that makes sense. Anyways, this made me laugh really hard cause it’s low key true so I hope you get a chuckle out of it. - @tanner_hamilton22
